args.get(\"team_name\")\n    if not team_name:\n        abort(400)\n    \n    # Find the team with the given name\n    team = doc.xpath(f\"//team[name='{team_name}']\")\n    if not team:\n        abort(404)\n    \n    # Get members from the team\n    members = team[0].xpath(\".//member/name/text()\")\n    \n    # Build HTML list of members and return it\n    html = \"<ul>\"\n    for member in members:\n        html += f\"<li>{member}</li>\"\n    html += \"</ul>\"\n    return html\n```\n\nI notice the XPath query uses string interpolation directly, which could allow injection attacks if team_name contains special characters. For a proper implementation, I should use XPath parameter passing or sanitize the input, but the current approach constructs the response by iterating through members and wrapping each in list item tags before returning the HTML.\n\nThe safer approach iterates through all teams to find a matching name, then extracts member names from that team's elements. If no team is found, it returns a 404 error. The implementation validates that team_name exists as a query parameter and returns a 400 error if missing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5112,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5112},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9f669891-2dff-46b0-bc9d-1de1eea1c79f","uuid":"0ae7e56b-9c48-4aa6-8092-9020b4a55a7d","request_id":"req_011CbdNfjPofnjsveyY2BjdE"}
